48   let random = bytes => crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(bytes))

50   let customRandom = (alphabet, defaultSize, getRandom) => {
51     // First, a bitmask is necessary to generate the ID. The bitmask makes bytes
52     // values closer to the alphabet size. The bitmask calculates the closest
53     // `2^31 - 1` number, which exceeds the alphabet size.
54     // For example, the bitmask for the alphabet size 30 is 31 (00011111).
55     // `Math.clz32` is not used, because it is not available in browsers.
56     let mask = (2 << (Math.log(alphabet.length - 1) / Math.LN2)) - 1
57     // Though, the bitmask solution is not perfect since the bytes exceeding
58     // the alphabet size are refused. Therefore, to reliably generate the ID,
59     // the random bytes redundancy has to be satisfied.
60   
61     // Note: every hardware random generator call is performance expensive,
62     // because the system call for entropy collection takes a lot of time.
63     // So, to avoid additional system calls, extra bytes are requested in advance.
64   
65     // Next, a step determines how many random bytes to generate.
66     // The number of random bytes gets decided upon the ID size, mask,
67     // alphabet size, and magic number 1.6 (using 1.6 peaks at performance
68     // according to benchmarks).
69   
70     // `-~f => Math.ceil(f)` if f is a float
71     // `-~i => i + 1` if i is an integer
72     let step = -~((1.6 * mask * defaultSize) / alphabet.length)
73   
74     return (size = defaultSize) => {
75       let id = ''
76       while (true) {
77         let bytes = getRandom(step)
78         // A compact alternative for `for (var i = 0; i < step; i++)`.
79         let j = step | 0
80         while (j--) {
81           // Adding `|| ''` refuses a random byte that exceeds the alphabet size.
82           id += alphabet[bytes[j] & mask] || ''
83           if (id.length === size) return id
84         }
85       }
86     }
87   }
88   
89   let customAlphabet = (alphabet, size = 21) =>
90     customRandom(alphabet, size, random)

92   let nanoid = (size = 21) =>
93     crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(size)).reduce((id, byte) => {
94       // It is incorrect to use bytes exceeding the alphabet size.
95       // The following mask reduces the random byte in the 0-255 value
96       // range to the 0-63 value range. Therefore, adding hacks, such
97       // as empty string fallback or magic numbers, is unneccessary because
98       // the bitmask trims bytes down to the alphabet size.
99       byte &= 63
100      if (byte < 36) {
101        // `0-9a-z`
102        id += byte.toString(36)
103      } else if (byte < 62) {
104        // `A-Z`
105        id += (byte - 26).toString(36).toUpperCase()
106      } else if (byte > 62) {
107        id += '-'
108      } else {
109        id += '_'
110      }
111      return id
112    }, '')

915  // Matches a string that ends in a . character, optionally followed by a sequence of
916  // digits followed by any number of 0 characters up until the end of the line.
917  // Ensuring that there is at least one prefixed character is important so that
918  // you don't incorrectly match against "0".
919  const trailingCharMatcherWithPrefix = /\.([0-9]*0)*$/;
920  // This is used for trimming the trailing 0 and . characters without affecting
921  // the rest of the string. Its possible to use one RegEx with groups for this
922  // functionality, but it is fairly complex compared to simply defining two
923  // different matchers.
924  const trailingCharMatcher = /[0.]0*$/;
925  /**
926   * The NumberField class has some special handling for dealing with trailing
927   * decimal points and/or zeroes. This logic is designed to allow trailing values
928   * to be visible in the input element, but not be represented in the
929   * corresponding form data.
930   *
931   * The algorithm is as follows:
932   *
933   * 1. When the input value changes the value is cached in the component state
934   *
935   * 2. The value is then normalized, removing trailing decimal points and zeros,
936   *    then passed to the "onChange" callback
937   *
938   * 3. When the component is rendered, the formData value is checked against the
939   *    value cached in the state. If it matches the cached value, the cached
940   *    value is passed to the input instead of the formData value
941   */
942  function NumberField(props) {
943      const { registry, onChange, formData, value: initialValue } = props;
944      const [lastValue, setLastValue] = (0,index_js_.useState)(initialValue);
945      const { StringField } = registry.fields;
946      let value = formData;
947      /** Handle the change from the `StringField` to properly convert to a number
948       *
949       * @param value - The current value for the change occurring
950       */
951      const handleChange = (0,index_js_.useCallback)((value) => {
952          // Cache the original value in component state
953          setLastValue(value);
954          // Normalize decimals that don't start with a zero character in advance so
955          // that the rest of the normalization logic is simpler
956          if (`${value}`.charAt(0) === '.') {
957              value = `0${value}`;
958          }
959          // Check that the value is a string (this can happen if the widget used is a
960          // <select>, due to an enum declaration etc) then, if the value ends in a
961          // trailing decimal point or multiple zeroes, strip the trailing values
962          const processed = typeof value === 'string' && value.match(trailingCharMatcherWithPrefix)
963              ? (0,lib_index_js_.asNumber)(value.replace(trailingCharMatcher, ''))
964              : (0,lib_index_js_.asNumber)(value);
965          onChange(processed);
966      }, [onChange]);
967      if (typeof lastValue === 'string' && typeof value === 'number') {
968          // Construct a regular expression that checks for a string that consists
969          // of the formData value suffixed with zero or one '.' characters and zero
970          // or more '0' characters
971          const re = new RegExp(`${value}`.replace('.', '\\.') + '\\.?0*$');
972          // If the cached "lastValue" is a match, use that instead of the formData
973          // value to prevent the input value from changing in the UI
974          if (lastValue.match(re)) {
975              value = lastValue;
976          }
977      }
978      return (0,jsx_runtime.jsx)(StringField, { ...props, formData: value, onChange: handleChange });
